npc1: My name is Ana. I used to teach math at the school down the street — before it closed.
npc1: My brother Dimas was 19 when a Bat led him to the app. He thought he was smart enough to beat the odds.
npc1: "It's just math, Kak," he told me.
npc1: Within six months, his university fund was gone. Every rupiah of it.
npc1: Then the Witch found him at his lowest. "Borrow from me. Win it all back," she said.
npc1: He borrowed. He lost. The debt grew. He borrowed again to cover the interest.
npc1: The worst part — he KNEW it was wrong. He told me so. But he could not stop.
npc1: That is what addiction does. It is not weakness. It rewires the brain's reward system until stopping feels impossible.
npc1: Now Dimas is somewhere in this city, working for her — paying a debt that never gets smaller.
npc1: I have not seen him in over a year.
npc1: Gambling addiction is a real medical condition. Please — if you know someone like him, do not wait.
npc1: Call 119 ext 8. That is the addiction helpline in Indonesia. Real help is there.
npc1: Real wealth is built slowly. Through education. Through work. Through patience.
npc1: Not from a slot machine. Not from anything that promises you the world in one click.
